      dek: `Before you register anything or pick a name, it helps to understand what a production company actually is — a business entity that makes films, and the legal and financial container your filmmaking lives inside.`,
      seoTitle: "What a Production Company Is: How to Start a Production Company | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "What a film production company actually is, what it does, and why filmmakers form one — the foundation for turning your filmmaking into a real business. Chapter 1 of Starting Your Production Company.",
      body: `<p>Everyone in film talks about "production companies" — A24, Blumhouse, the little logo that plays before the movie — but when you're starting out it's worth being clear about what one actually is. Here's the plain version: <strong>a production company is a business entity, most commonly a limited liability company (LLC) or corporation, that exists to produce films and other content — it's the legal and financial container your filmmaking work lives inside, the thing that signs contracts, holds the rights, hires the crew, and receives the money.</strong> When you make a film "as a company" rather than as yourself personally, that company is what enters into agreements with investors, distributors, cast, and crew; it's what owns (or licenses) the film's copyright; it's what has a bank account the budget flows through; and it's what shields your personal assets if something goes wrong. A production company isn't a building or a staff of hundreds — for most independent filmmakers it starts as a single-member LLC with one person (you) and a name. But that simple legal wrapper changes everything about how professionally, safely, and sustainably you can operate. This whole course is about setting one up well; this first chapter is just about understanding what it is and what it does.</p>

<h2>What a production company actually does</h2>

<p>The core functions a production company serves:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Signs contracts.</b> The company — not you personally — enters agreements with cast, crew, investors, locations, and distributors.</li>
  <li><b>Holds the rights.</b> It owns or controls the film's copyright and underlying rights, keeping ownership clear and in one place.</li>
  <li><b>Handles the money.</b> Budgets, payments, and revenue flow through the company's bank account and books, separate from your personal finances.</li>
  <li><b>Limits your liability.</b> As a separate legal entity (like an LLC), it helps shield your personal assets if the production faces debts or lawsuits.</li>
  <li><b>Provides structure for taxes.</b> It gives you a clean business structure for deductions, accounting, and tax treatment (with a professional's help).</li>
  <li><b>Signals professionalism.</b> Operating as a company tells investors, partners, and crew that you're a serious, credible operation.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The container your filmmaking lives in</h2>

<p>The most useful way to picture a production company is as <strong>a container — a legal and financial box that holds your film project, keeps it separate from your personal life, and lets it interact with the world as a business rather than as one person's hobby.</strong> Think about what happens when you make a film without a company: you personally sign every contract, your personal bank account holds the budget, your personal name owns the copyright, and if a crew member gets hurt or an investor sues, your personal assets — your savings, your car, your home — are on the line. Now put a company around the project: the company signs the contracts, the company's account holds the money, the company owns the film, and (properly set up) the company's liability is separate from yours. That separation is the single biggest reason production companies exist, and we'll dig into it in the next chapter. But the container does more than protect you — it also organizes you. Money in and out has a clear home, so your accounting is clean. The film's rights sit in one entity, so ownership is never murky. Contracts are all signed by the same party, so there's consistency. And when you talk to an investor or a distributor, you're a company doing business with them, not an individual asking a favor — which changes how seriously you're taken. A couple of honest points to set expectations. First, <em>a production company can be tiny</em> — for most people reading this, it's a one-person LLC, not an office with staff, so don't let the word "company" intimidate you. Second, <em>it's a wrapper, not magic</em> — forming a company doesn't make your film good or get it funded; it's the professional container that makes everything else — funding, contracts, protection — work properly, which is exactly why serious filmmakers set one up. Third, <em>the details matter and vary</em> — how you form and run the company involves legal and tax choices that differ by where you live, so throughout this course I'll flag where you need a professional (this is general education, not legal, tax, or financial advice). A production company is the business entity your filmmaking lives inside: it signs, owns, banks, and protects. Understanding that is the foundation. We'll look at why you'd actually want one — the concrete reasons filmmakers make it official. Next, why start a production company.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A production company is the container your filmmaking lives inside — the entity that signs the contracts, owns the film, holds the money, and shields you personally. It can be as small as a one-person LLC. But that simple wrapper changes everything.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>For my first couple of shorts, I <em>was</em> the production company — my name on every release form, my personal checking account funding the shoot, my signature on the location agreement. It worked until it almost didn't: a piece of gear got damaged at a rented location and suddenly there was a dispute with real money attached, pointed straight at me personally. That was the moment I understood what a production company is <em>for</em>. When I formed an LLC and made the next film through it, everything felt different — the contracts were cleaner, the money had a home, and I wasn't personally exposed. Nothing about my filmmaking changed. Everything about the business around it did. That's what this course is really about.</p>
</div>`,
