      dek: `Not every filmmaker needs a company today. This chapter gives you the honest signals for when it's time — and when you can happily wait — so you form one because you actually need it, not because a checklist told you to.`,
      seoTitle: "Do You Need One Yet? When to Start a Production Company | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "How to know when it's the right time to form your film production company — the signals that you've outgrown working as an individual, and when you can wait. Chapter 4 of Starting Your Production Company.",
      body: `<p>Now that you know what a production company is and why they exist, here's a question the internet rarely answers honestly: do you need one <em>right now</em>? And the truthful answer is — <strong>you should form a production company when the reasons for one actually apply to you: when you're taking on real financial or legal exposure, raising or handling other people's money, hiring crew, signing meaningful contracts, or building an ongoing filmmaking business — and you can reasonably wait if you're still making tiny, low-risk personal projects with no outside money involved.</strong> There's no universal "you must incorporate now" moment, and forming a company too early just means paying fees and doing paperwork for protection you don't yet need. But there's a real danger in waiting too long — signing a big location agreement or taking an investor's check as an individual, and discovering your personal exposure only when something goes wrong. So this chapter is about reading the signals honestly, so you form one at the right time: not out of anxiety, and not too late. Let's look at the signs.</p>

<h2>Signs it's time to form one</h2>

<p>Signals that you've outgrown working as an individual:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Other people's money is involved.</b> You're raising investment, taking pre-sales, or handling a real budget that isn't just your own pocket cash.</li>
  <li><b>You're hiring crew or cast.</b> People working on your production create real responsibility and potential liability that a company helps contain.</li>
  <li><b>You're signing meaningful contracts.</b> Locations, distribution, gear, talent — agreements with real money and risk attached, that you'd rather sign as a company.</li>
  <li><b>Your projects have real value.</b> A film worth protecting — copyright, potential revenue — belongs in an entity, not just in your personal name.</li>
  <li><b>You're building something ongoing.</b> You're moving from one-off projects to a continuing body of work and want a professional home and track record for it.</li>
  <li><b>You want the tax structure.</b> Your film income and expenses are large enough that a proper business structure starts to make financial sense (per your accountant).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Reading the signals honestly</h2>

<p>The healthy way to make this call is to look at your <em>next</em> project rather than your last one, and ask <strong>whether the exposure, the money, the people, and the ambition have reached the point where operating as an individual is genuinely riskier or more limiting than operating as a company — because that crossover point, not a fixed date, is when you form one.</strong> If your honest answer is "I'm making a $300 short with two friends, no outside money, no rented location, just for the festival circuit," then you probably don't need to rush — you can wait, keep learning, and form a company when the stakes rise. But the moment any of the signals show up — an investor is ready to write a check, you're about to hire a crew of ten, you're negotiating a location agreement with real liability, or you're sitting on a finished film with genuine commercial value in your personal name — that's the crossover, and it's time. The biggest mistake I see isn't forming too early; it's waiting too long and taking on serious exposure as an individual because setting up a company felt like a hassle. A few honest points to guide the timing. First, <em>form it before the exposure, not after</em> — the protection only helps if the company exists when you sign the contract or take the money, so if a real project is coming, get the company in place ahead of it rather than scrambling later. Second, <em>don't let "not yet" become "never"</em> — it's fine to wait while you're small, but keep checking against the signals, because ambition tends to sneak up and you don't want to be caught operating personally on something serious. Third, <em>when in doubt, ask a professional</em> — a short conversation with a lawyer or accountant about your specific situation will tell you far more than any general checklist about whether now is your moment (general education, not legal or tax advice). You form a production company when the reasons apply — real money, crew, contracts, value, or an ongoing business — and you can wait while you're still tiny and low-risk. Read the signals honestly, and form it just ahead of the exposure. That closes the Foundations module. In Module 2 we get practical, starting with the fun part: naming and branding your company. Next, naming and branding your company.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The biggest mistake isn't forming a company too early — it's waiting too long and signing the big contract or taking the investor's check as an individual, then discovering your personal exposure only when something goes wrong. Form it just ahead of the risk.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I've made this call both ways. Early on, I formed a company way too eagerly for a film that ended up being a tiny personal project — paid the fees, filed the paperwork, and barely used it. Lesson learned: don't incorporate out of excitement. But the more expensive lesson came the other direction, watching a friend take a five-figure investor check into his personal account for a film with no company around it. When the project hit trouble, that exposure was all his, personally. He'd told himself he'd "set up the company later." Now I use a simple rule: the moment real money or real people enter a project, the company goes in place <em>first</em>. Not too early out of anxiety, not too late out of laziness — right when the stakes cross the line.</p>
</div>`,
