      body: `<p>Naming your production company is genuinely fun — it's the moment the whole thing starts to feel real — but it trips up more filmmakers than they expect, because a name has to satisfy several masters at once. Here's the principle: <strong>a good production company name works on three levels simultaneously — it's legally available (not already taken or trademarked by someone else), it's brandable and memorable (easy to say, spell, and remember, and it feels right for the kind of films you make), and it's available online (the domain and social handles you'd want are free) — and the trick is finding a name that clears all three, not just the one you fell in love with.</strong> Plenty of people pick a name they love, register the company, and then discover the domain is taken, the handle belongs to someone else, or worse, another production company already uses it and could raise a legal objection. So the smart move is to check all three before you commit. And once you've got the name, a bit of light branding — a consistent look and feel — makes the company feel professional from day one. This chapter walks through both.</p>

<h2>What a good name needs to clear</h2>

<p>The three tests every candidate name should pass:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Legally available.</b> Not already registered as a business in your jurisdiction, and not infringing an existing trademark — check before you commit (and confirm with a professional).</li>
  <li><b>Brandable &amp; memorable.</b> Easy to say, spell, and remember; feels right for your films; not easily confused with a well-known company.</li>
  <li><b>Available online.</b> The .com (or your preferred domain) and the social handles you'd want are free or reasonably obtainable.</li>
  <li><b>Not too limiting.</b> Broad enough to grow with you — a name tied to one genre or one project can box you in later.</li>
  <li><b>Not a legal headache.</b> Avoid names that could be confused with major studios or existing companies — that's a trademark risk you don't want.</li>
</ul>

<h2>From name to a brand that feels real</h2>

<p>The workflow that actually gets you to a good name is to <strong>brainstorm broadly, then run your favorites through all three tests — legal, brand, and online availability — and only commit to a name that survives all of them, because a name that fails even one becomes a problem later.</strong> Start by generating a big list without judging — words that evoke the feeling of your films, your own name, places, images, invented words — quantity first. Then filter for <em>brandability</em>: say each one out loud, imagine it before a film, imagine telling someone at a festival; cut the ones that are hard to spell, easy to mishear, or feel wrong. Then do the <em>availability</em> checks on your finalists: search business registries to see if the name is taken in your area, do a basic trademark search, and check whether the domain and handles are free — because discovering the .com is gone <em>after</em> you've registered the company is a needless headache. (Anything that touches trademarks or legal availability is worth confirming with a professional — this is general education, not legal advice.) Once a name clears all three, you've got your company's identity, and a little branding turns it into something that feels real: a simple, consistent visual identity — which we'll cover properly in the next chapter on your logo — plus consistent use of the name across your email, your documents, and your online presence. A few honest points. First, <em>don't fall in love before you check</em> — the heartbreak of losing a name you'd already committed to is avoidable; run the three tests <em>before</em> you register anything. Second, <em>simpler and broader usually wins</em> — a clean, easy name that isn't locked to one genre or project will serve you across a whole career, while a clever, narrow, or hard-to-spell one tends to age badly. Third, <em>watch the trademark trap</em> — a name that echoes a major studio or an existing company might feel flattering but is a real legal risk, so steer clear and confirm anything doubtful with a professional. A good production company name clears three tests at once — legally available, brandable, and free online — and a bit of consistent branding makes the company feel real. With a name that works, the next chapter turns to the face of your brand: your logo and visual identity. Next, your logo and visual identity.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A good name works on three levels at once — legally available, brandable and memorable, and free as a domain and handle. Don't fall in love before you've checked all three, because a name that fails even one becomes a problem you'll pay for later.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I named my first company after a clever little in-joke I adored. I registered the business, ordered nothing, and then went to grab the domain — gone. The handle — gone. And when I searched, there was already a small production outfit two states over using almost the same name. I'd fallen in love before I'd checked, and I had to start over. The second time, I did it in the right order: brainstormed a long list, said each one out loud, checked the registry and a basic trademark search, and only <em>then</em> confirmed the domain and handles were free — and committed to the one name that passed everything. It's less romantic to check first. It's also the only way to keep the name you pick.</p>
</div>`,
