      seoTitle: "Your Website & Online Presence: Film Production Company Website | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "How to build a film production company website and online presence that makes you findable and credible — what pages you need and how to keep it simple and professional. Chapter 11 of Starting Your Production Company.",
      body: `<p>The moment someone serious hears your company's name — an investor considering a check, a distributor weighing a deal, a talented crew member deciding whether to work with you — their next move is predictable: they look you up online. So here's the principle: <strong>your website and online presence are your company's storefront and credibility check — the place people go to confirm you're real, see your work, and get in touch — and a simple, clean, professional presence (a basic website plus consistent social profiles) makes you findable and trustworthy, while having nothing, or something sloppy, quietly costs you opportunities.</strong> The good news is that this doesn't need to be elaborate. A production company website isn't a complex product; it's a clear, professional page that shows who you are, shows your work, and lets people reach you — and you can build a perfectly credible one on a small budget with modern tools. What matters is that it exists, looks intentional (using the logo and brand from earlier chapters), and covers the essentials. The mistake is either having no online presence at all (so you look unfindable or not real) or having a messy, half-finished one (which is worse than nothing). This chapter covers what your presence needs.</p>

<h2>What your online presence needs</h2>

<p>The essentials of a credible company presence:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>A simple website.</b> Clean and professional, using your logo and brand — the anchor of your online presence and the address you can put on everything.</li>
  <li><b>Your work / portfolio.</b> Show the films or projects you've made (or are making) — trailers, stills, links. This is what people actually want to see.</li>
  <li><b>An about page.</b> Who the company is and what it makes — your focus and voice, so people understand what you're about.</li>
  <li><b>Clear contact info.</b> An easy way to reach you — a professional email at your domain looks far better than a personal free address.</li>
  <li><b>Consistent social profiles.</b> The handles you secured when naming the company, kept consistent and reasonably active where it makes sense for your work.</li>
  <li><b>Findable &amp; consistent.</b> Your name, logo, and links consistent everywhere, so people who search for you find a coherent, professional picture.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Keeping it simple and professional</h2>

<p>The right approach is to build <strong>the simplest presence that credibly answers "who is this company, what have they made, and how do I reach them?" — clean, on-brand, and easy to find — rather than an elaborate site you'll never finish.</strong> Start with a basic <em>website</em>: it doesn't need to be fancy, just clean and professional, using the logo and brand kit from Module 2 so it looks like a real company. The most important content is your <em>work</em> — a portfolio of what you've made or are making, because that's what investors, distributors, and collaborators actually want to evaluate — plus a short <em>about</em> section and clear <em>contact</em> info (with a professional email at your own domain, which is a small touch that meaningfully raises how serious you look). Then extend to <em>social</em>: use the handles you secured when you named the company, keep them consistent with your brand, and be active where it genuinely serves your work — you don't need to be everywhere, just coherent and findable. The throughline, as with branding, is consistency: the same name, logo, and links everywhere, so anyone who looks you up finds a professional, unified picture. A few honest points. First, <em>having something simple beats having nothing</em> — an unfindable company looks unreal or unserious, so a clean basic site is a real competitive advantage over the many filmmakers who skip it. Second, <em>a messy site is worse than none</em> — a half-finished, broken, or sloppy presence actively damages credibility, so either do a simple thing well or don't do it yet; polish over ambition. Third, <em>a domain email is a cheap credibility win</em> — replacing a personal free email with one at your own domain instantly makes you look more established, for very little effort. Fourth, <em>keep it consistent and current</em> — the same brand everywhere, and update your work as you make it, so the picture people find stays coherent and alive. Your website and online presence are your storefront and credibility check — keep them simple, on-brand, findable, and above all professional. With your company presented well to the world, the final chapter looks ahead to building it into something that lasts. Next, building and growing your company.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The moment someone serious hears your company's name, they look you up. A clean, simple, findable presence quietly wins you credibility — while nothing, or something sloppy, quietly costs you opportunities you'll never even know you missed.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once lost a collaboration before I even knew I was in the running. Months later, the person told me: they'd heard about my company, gone to look it up — and found nothing. No website, an inconsistent handle, a personal Gmail address on an old post. They quietly assumed I wasn't a serious, ongoing operation and went with someone else. Nothing about my actual work was the problem; my <em>findability</em> was. I built a simple site that weekend — logo, a few projects, an about paragraph, a contact email at my own domain — and secured my handles to match. It took a fraction of the effort I'd feared, and I've watched it do quiet work ever since: people look me up, find something clean and real, and take the next meeting. Simple and professional beats invisible every time.</p>
</div>`,
